# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gpu-driven-rendering
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] A hidden-surface determination algorithm is a solution to the visibility problem, which was one of the first major problems in the field of 3D computer graphics.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] The process of hidden-surface determination is sometimes called **hiding**, and such an algorithm is sometimes called a **hider**.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] When referring to line rendering it is known as hidden-line removal.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] Hidden-surface determination is necessary to render a scene correctly, so that one may not view features hidden behind the model itself, allowing only the naturally viewable portion of the graphic to be visible.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] Hidden-surface determination is a process that identifies which surfaces are not visible to the user (for example, because they lie behind opaque objects such as walls).
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] Despite advances in hardware capability, rendering algorithms require substantial computational resources.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] By deciding that certain surfaces do not need to be rendered because they are not visible, rendering engines can improve efficiency, allowing the rendering of large world spaces.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] There are many techniques for hidden-surface determination, but they generally rely on sorting the surfaces based on their distance from the viewer.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] Sorting large quantities of graphics primitives can be computationally-expensive and is usually done by divide and conquer.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] The different hidden-surface determination techniques differ, in part, through the way in which the space is partitioned prior to sorting.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] A rendering pipeline typically entails the following steps: projection, clipping, and rasterization.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] is used) is checked against an existing depth value.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] If the current pixel is behind the pixel in the Z-buffer, the pixel is rejected, otherwise, it is shaded and its depth value replaces the one in the Z-buffer.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] Z-buffering supports dynamic scenes easily and is currently implemented efficiently in graphics hardware.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] Z-buffering requires up to 4 bytes per pixel, and can have a substantial computational cost since the rasterization algorithm needs to check each rasterized sample against the Z-buffer.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] , these approaches store information about already displayed segments for each line of the screen (in contrast of storing each pixel as is the case for Z-buffering).
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] New polygons are then cut against already displayed segments that would hide them.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] An S-buffer can display unsorted polygons, while a C-buffer requires polygons to be displayed from the nearest to the furthest.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] Because the C-buffer technique does not require a pixel to be drawn more than once, the process is slightly faster.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] Polygons are displayed from the nearest to the furthest.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] New polygons are clipped against already displayed polygons' edges, creating new polygons to display, then storing the additional edges.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] Such an approach is harder to implement than S/C/Z-buffers, but it scales much better with increased image resolution.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] The drawbacks are the computational cost of the sorting step and the fact that visual artifacts can occur.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] This algorithm can fail for general scenes, as it cannot handle polygons in various common configurations, such as surfaces that intersect each other.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] This technique divides a scene along planes corresponding to polygon boundaries.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] The subdivision is constructed in such a way as to provide an unambiguous depth ordering from any point in the scene when the BSP tree is traversed.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] The main disadvantage of the technique is the high computational cost of the construction of the BSP tree.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] As a result, this approach is less suitable for scenes consisting of dynamic geometry.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] The advantage of BSP is that the data is pre-sorted and error-free, and can be used as input for the previously mentioned algorithms.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] Note that the BSP is not a solution to hidden-surface removal, only an aid.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] Ray tracing attempts to model the path of light rays to a viewpoint by tracing rays from the viewpoint into the scene.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] Although not a hidden-surface removal algorithm as such, it implicitly solves the hidden-surface removal problem by finding the nearest surface along each view-ray.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] Effectively this approach is equivalent to sorting all the geometry on a per-pixel basis.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] This algorithm divides the screen into smaller areas and sorts triangles within these.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] If there is ambiguity (i.e., polygons overlap in-depth extent within these areas), then further subdivision occurs.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] At the limit, the subdivision may occur down to the pixel level.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] A related area to visible-surface determination is *culling*, which usually happens before visible-surface determination in a rendering pipeline.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] Primitives or batches of primitives can be rejected in their entirety, which *usually* reduces the computational load in a rendering system.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] The viewing frustum is a geometric representation of the volume visible to the virtual camera.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] Naturally, objects outside this volume will not be visible in the final image, so they are discarded.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] Often, objects lie on the boundary of the viewing frustum.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] These objects are cut into pieces along this boundary in a process called clipping, and the pieces that lie outside the frustum are discarded as there is no place to draw them.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] With 3D objects, some of the object's surface is facing the camera, and the rest is facing away from the camera, i.e. is on the backside of the object, hindered by the front side.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] If the object is completely opaque, those surfaces never need to be drawn.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] These surfaces are determined by the vertex winding order: if the triangle drawn has its vertices in clockwise order on the projection plane when facing the camera, they switch into counter-clockwise order when the surface turns away from the camera.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] Incidentally, this approach also makes the objects completely transparent when the viewpoint camera is located inside them, because then all the surfaces of the object are facing away from the camera and are culled by the renderer.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] To prevent this artifact, the object must be set as double-sided (i.e. no back-face culling is done) or have separate inside surfaces.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] Often, objects are so far away that they do not contribute significantly to the final image.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] These objects are thrown away if their screen projection is too small.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] Objects that are entirely behind other opaque objects may be culled.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] This is a very popular mechanism to speed up the rendering of large scenes that have a moderate to high depth complexity.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] A popular theme in the visible surface determination literature is divide and conquer.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] The Warnock algorithm pioneered dividing the screen.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] Beam tracing is a ray-tracing approach that divides the visible volumes into beams.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] Various screen-space subdivision approaches reduce the number of primitives considered per region, e.g. tiling, or screen-space BSP clipping.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] Tiling may be used as a preprocess to other techniques.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] Z-buffer hardware may typically include a coarse "hi-Z", against which primitives can be rejected early without rasterization.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] Such an approach is a form of occlusion culling.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] Bounding volume hierarchies (BVHs) are often used to subdivide the scene's space (examples are the BSP tree, the octree and the kd-tree).
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] This approach allows visibility determination to be performed hierarchically: if a node in the tree is considered to be *invisible*, then all of its child nodes are also invisible, and no further processing is necessary (they can all be rejected by the renderer).
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] If a node is considered *visible*, then each of its children needs to be evaluated.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/frustum-culling] This traversal is effectively a tree walk, where invisibility/occlusion or reaching a leaf node determines whether to stop or whether to recurse, respectively.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/primitive-geometry] In vector computer graphics, CAD systems, and geographic information systems, a **geometric primitive** (or **prim**) is the simplest (i.e.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/primitive-geometry] 'atomic' or irreducible) geometric shape that the system can handle (draw, store).
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/primitive-geometry] Sometimes the subroutines that draw the corresponding objects are called "geometric primitives" as well.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/primitive-geometry] The most "primitive" primitives are point and straight line segments, which were all that early vector graphics systems had.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/primitive-geometry] In constructive solid geometry, primitives are simple geometric shapes such as a cube, cylinder, sphere, cone, pyramid, torus.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/primitive-geometry] Modern 2D computer graphics systems may operate with primitives which are curves (segments of straight lines, circles and more complicated curves), as well as shapes (boxes, arbitrary polygons, circles).
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/primitive-geometry] A common set of two-dimensional primitives includes lines, points, and polygons, although some people prefer to consider triangles primitives, because every polygon can be constructed from triangles (polygon triangulation).
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/primitive-geometry] All other graphic elements are built up from these primitives.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/primitive-geometry] In three dimensions, triangles or polygons positioned in three-dimensional space can be used as primitives to model more complex 3D forms.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/primitive-geometry] In some cases, curves (such as Bézier curves, circles, etc.) may be considered primitives; in other cases, curves are complex forms created from many straight, primitive shapes.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/primitive-geometry] In GIS, the terrain surface is often spoken of colloquially as "2 1/2 dimensional," because only the upper surface needs to be represented.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/primitive-geometry] Thus, elevation can be conceptualized as a scalar field property or function of two-dimensional space, affording it a number of data modeling efficiencies over true 3-dimensional objects.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/primitive-geometry] A shape of any of these dimensions greater than zero consists of an infinite number of distinct points.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/primitive-geometry] Because digital systems are finite, only a sample set of the points in a shape can be stored.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/primitive-geometry] Thus, vector data structures typically represent geometric primitives using a strategic sample, organized in structures that facilitate the software interpolating the remainder of the shape at the time of analysis or display, using the algorithms of Computational geometry.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/primitive-geometry] A wide variety of vector data structures and formats have been developed during the history of Geographic information systems, but they share a fundamental basis of storing a core set of geometric primitives to represent the location and extent of geographic phenomena.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/primitive-geometry] Locations of points are almost always measured within a standard Earth-based coordinate system, whether the spherical Geographic coordinate system (latitude/longitude), or a planar coordinate system, such as the Universal Transverse Mercator.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/primitive-geometry] They also share the need to store a set of attributes of each geographic feature alongside its shape; traditionally, this has been accomplished using the data models, data formats, and even software of relational databases.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/primitive-geometry] Early vector formats, such as POLYVRT, the ARC/INFO Coverage, and the Esri shapefile support a basic set of geometric primitives: points, polylines, and polygons, only in two dimensional space and the latter two with only straight line interpolation.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/primitive-geometry] TIN data structures for representing terrain surfaces as triangle meshes were also added.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/primitive-geometry] Since the mid 1990s, new formats have been developed that extend the range of available primitives, generally standardized by the Open Geospatial Consortium's Simple Features specification.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/primitive-geometry] Frequently, a representation of the shape of a real-world phenomenon may have a different (usually lower) dimension than the phenomenon being represented.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/primitive-geometry] For example, a city (a two-dimensional region) may be represented as a point, or a road (a three-dimensional volume of material) may be represented as a line.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/primitive-geometry] This dimensional generalization correlates with tendencies in spatial cognition.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/primitive-geometry] For example, asking the distance between two cities presumes a conceptual model of the cities as points, while giving directions involving travel "up," "down," or "along" a road imply a one-dimensional conceptual model.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/primitive-geometry] In CAD software or 3D modelling, the interface may present the user with the ability to create primitives which may be further modified by edits.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/primitive-geometry] For example, in the practice of box modelling the user will start with a cuboid, then use extrusion and other operations to create the model.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/primitive-geometry] In this use the primitive is just a convenient starting point, rather than the fundamental unit of modelling.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/primitive-geometry] A 3D package may also include a list of extended primitives which are more complex shapes that come with the package.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/primitive-geometry] For example, a teapot is listed as a primitive in 3D Studio Max.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/primitive-geometry] Various graphics accelerators exist with hardware acceleration for rendering specific primitives such as lines or triangles, frequently with texture mapping and shaders.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/primitive-geometry] Modern 3D accelerators typically accept sequences of triangles as triangle strips.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rasterisation] In computer graphics, **rasterisation** (British English) or **rasterization** (American English) is the task of taking an image described in a vector graphics format (shapes) and converting it into a raster image which represents the original image.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rasterisation] The rasterized image may then be displayed on a computer display, video display or printer, or stored in a bitmap file format.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rasterisation] Rasterization may refer to the technique of drawing 3D models, or to the conversion of 2D rendering primitives, such as polygons and line segments, into a rasterized format.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rasterisation] The term "rasterisation" comes from German *Raster* 'grid, pattern, schema' and Latin *rāstrum* 'scraper, rake'.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rasterisation] Bresenham's line algorithm is an example of an algorithm used to rasterize lines.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rasterisation] Algorithms such as the midpoint circle algorithm are used to render circles onto a pixelated canvas.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rasterisation] Polygons are a common representation of digital 3D models.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rasterisation] Before rasterization, individual polygons are triangulated - therefore, a typical problem to solve in 3D rasterization is rasterization of a triangle.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rasterisation] 2. no pixel is rasterized more than once, i.e. the rasterized triangles don't overlap.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rasterisation] This is to guarantee that the result doesn't depend on the order in which the triangles are rasterized.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rasterisation] Overdrawing pixels can also mean wasting computing power on pixels that would be overwritten.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rasterisation] This leads to establishing **rasterization rules** to guarantee the above conditions.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rasterisation] 2. its center lies exactly on the triangle edge (or multiple edges in case of corners) – that is (or, in case of corners, all are), either the *top* or *left* edge.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rasterisation] A *top* edge is an edge that is exactly horizontal and lies above other edges, and a *left* edge is a non-horizontal edge that is on the left side of the triangle.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rasterisation] This rule decides which triangle a pixel on a boundary belongs to.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rasterisation] It is implemented by Direct3D and OpenGL (although the specification here only requires a consistent rule).
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rasterisation] Rasterization is one of the typical techniques of rendering 3D models.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rasterisation] Compared with other rendering techniques such as ray tracing, rasterization is extremely fast and therefore used in most realtime 3D engines.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rasterisation] However, rasterization is simply the process of computing the mapping from scene geometry to pixels and does not prescribe a particular way to compute the color of those pixels.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rasterisation] The specific color of each pixel is assigned by a pixel shader (which in modern GPUs is completely programmable).
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rasterisation] Shading may take into account physical effects such as light position, their approximations or purely artistic intent.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rasterisation] The process of rasterizing 3D models onto a 2D plane for display on a computer screen ("screen space") is often carried out by fixed function (non-programmable) hardware within the graphics pipeline.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rasterisation] This is because there is no motivation for modifying the techniques for rasterization used at render time and a special-purpose system allows for high efficiency.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rasterisation] The quality of rasterization can be improved by antialiasing, which creates "smooth" edges.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rasterisation] Sub-pixel precision is a method which takes into account positions on a finer scale than the pixel grid and can produce different results even if the endpoints of a primitive fall into same pixel coordinates, producing smoother movement animations.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rasterisation] Simple or older hardware, such as PlayStation 1, lacked sub-pixel precision in 3D rasterization.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In a computer graphics context, in standard usage, the word "rendering" by itself means rendering 3D scenes, but it is sometimes used with a broader meaning.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A modifier such as "2D" or "3D" is used when there is potential ambiguity (e.g.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A software application or component that performs rendering is called a **rendering engine**, **render engine**, **rendering system**, **graphics engine**, or simply a **renderer**.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A distinction is made between real-time rendering, in which images are generated and displayed immediately (ideally fast enough to give the impression of motion or animation), and offline rendering (sometimes called pre-rendering) in which images or film frames, are generated for later viewing.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Offline rendering can use a slower and higher-quality renderer.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Interactive applications such as games must primarily use real-time rendering, although they may incorporate pre-rendered content.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Rendering produces images of scenes or objects defined using coordinates in 3D space, seen from a particular viewpoint.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] It uses knowledge and ideas from optics, the study of visual perception, mathematics, and software engineering, and it has applications such as video games, simulators, visual effects for films and television, design visualization, and medical diagnosis.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Realistic rendering requires modeling the propagation of light in an environment, e.g. by applying the rendering equation.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Real-time rendering uses high-performance *rasterization* algorithms that process a list of shapes and determine which pixels are covered by each shape.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] When more realism is required (e.g. for architectural visualization or visual effects) slower pixel-by-pixel algorithms such as *ray tracing* are used instead.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] (Ray tracing can also be used selectively during rasterized rendering to improve the realism of lighting and reflections.) A type of ray tracing called *path tracing* is currently the most common technique for photorealistic rendering.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Path tracing is also popular for generating high-quality non-photorealistic images, such as frames for 3D animated films.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Both rasterization and ray tracing can be sped up ("accelerated") by specially designed microprocessors called GPUs.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Rasterization algorithms are also used to produce images containing only 2D shapes such as polygons and text.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] This type of rendering is sometimes called *2D rendering*, and its applications include digital illustration, graphic design, 2D animation, desktop publishing and the display of user interfaces.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Historically, rendering was called **image synthesis** but today this term is likely to mean AI image generation.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The term "neural rendering" is sometimes used when a neural network is the primary means of generating an image but some degree of control over the output image is provided.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Neural networks can also assist rendering without replacing traditional algorithms, e.g. by removing noise from path traced images.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A large proportion of computer graphics research has worked towards producing images that resemble photographs.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Fundamental techniques that make this possible were invented in the 1980s, but at the end of the decade, photorealism for complex scenes was still considered a distant goal.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Today, photorealism is routinely achievable for offline rendering, but remains difficult for real-time rendering.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In order to produce realistic images, rendering must simulate how light travels from light sources, is reflected, refracted, and scattered (often many times) by objects in the scene, passes through a camera lens, and finally reaches the film or sensor of the camera.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The physics used in these simulations is primarily geometrical optics, in which particles of light follow (usually straight) lines called *rays*, but in some situations (such as when rendering thin films, like the surface of soap bubbles) the wave nature of light must be taken into account.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In realistic scenes, objects are illuminated both by light that arrives directly from a light source (after passing mostly unimpeded through air), and light that has bounced off other objects in the scene.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The simulation of this complex lighting is called global illumination.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In the past, indirect lighting was often faked (especially when rendering animated films) by placing additional hidden lights in the scene, but today path tracing is used to render it accurately.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] For true photorealism, the camera used to take the photograph must be simulated.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The *thin lens approximation* allows combining perspective projection with depth of field (and bokeh) emulation.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Camera lens simulations can be made more realistic by modeling the way light is refracted by the components of the lens.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Motion blur is often simulated if film or video frames are being rendered.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Simulated lens flare and bloom are sometimes added to make the image appear subjectively brighter (although the design of real cameras tries to reduce these effects).
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Realistic rendering uses mathematical descriptions of how different surface materials reflect light, called *reflectance models* or (when physically plausible) *bidirectional reflectance distribution functions (BRDFs)*.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Rendering materials such as marble, plant leaves, and human skin requires simulating an effect called subsurface scattering, in which a portion of the light travels into the material, is scattered, and then travels back out again.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The way color, and properties such as roughness, vary over a surface can be represented efficiently using texture mapping.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] For some applications (including early stages of 3D modeling), simplified rendering styles such as wireframe rendering may be appropriate, particularly when the material and surface details have not been defined and only the shape of an object is known.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Games and other real-time applications may use simpler and less realistic rendering techniques as an artistic or design choice, or to allow higher frame rates on lower-end hardware.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Orthographic and isometric projections can be used for a stylized effect or to ensure that parallel lines are depicted as parallel in CAD rendering.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Non-photorealistic rendering (NPR) uses techniques like edge detection and posterization to produce 3D images that resemble technical illustrations, cartoons, or other styles of drawing or painting.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In 2D computer graphics the positions and sizes of shapes are specified using 2D coordinates (x and y) instead of 3D coordinates (x, y, and z).
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] 2D rendering APIs often use a resolution-independent coordinate system, with a viewport determining how to convert coordinates to pixel indexes called *device coordinates*.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Transformations such as scaling, translation, and rotation may be applied before rendering the shapes.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] These affine transformations are often represented by 3 × 3 matrices, allowing easier composition of transformations.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Higher-quality 2D rendering engines such as SVG renderers usually implement anti-aliasing to reduce the jagged appearance of rasterized lines and shape edges.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] When rendering overlapping shapes, renderers commonly use a "painter's model" in which the shapes are drawn in some determined order, or their contributions to each pixel are composited using blending operations that may depend on the order of the inputs.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Renderers may allow giving shapes a "z index" or "stacking order" to specify the rendering or blending order (unlike the z coordinate used in 3D rendering, this third coordinate only indicates an order, not a distance, and cannot be meaningfully rotated together with the x and y coordinates).
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] 2D rendering typically does not simulate light propagation (which would likely require specifying 3D positions or thickness for the shapes).
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Effects such as drop shadows and transparency are defined by mathematical functions with no physical basis.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] 2D rendering for print output may need to support very high resolutions, e.g.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] 600 or 1200 DPI for a typical laser printer, or 2400 DPI or higher for an imagesetter or platesetter.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Grayscale and color images require halftones (or some form of dithering or stochastic screening) and color separations.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A rendering engine called a *raster image processor* (RIP) converts input data such as PDF files into the high-resolution bitmap images used by the printer.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Before a 3D scene or 2D image can be rendered, it must be described in a way that the rendering software can understand.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Historically, inputs for both 2D and 3D rendering were usually text files, which are easier than binary files for humans to edit and debug.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Traditional rendering algorithms use geometric descriptions of 3D scenes or 2D images.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Applications and algorithms that render visualizations of data scanned from the real world, or scientific simulations, may require different types of input data.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The PostScript format (which is often credited with the rise of desktop publishing) provides a standardized, interoperable way to describe 2D graphics and page layout.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The Scalable Vector Graphics (SVG) format is also text-based, and the PDF format uses the PostScript language internally.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Many file formats exist for storing individual 3D objects or "models".
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] These can be imported into a larger scene, or loaded on-demand by rendering software or games.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A realistic scene may require hundreds of items like household objects, vehicles, and trees, and 3D artists often utilize large libraries of models.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In game production, these models (along with other data such as textures, audio files, and animations) are referred to as "assets".
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Scientific and engineering visualization often requires rendering volumetric data generated by 3D scans or simulations.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Perhaps the most common source of such data is medical CT and MRI scans, which need to be rendered for diagnosis.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Volumetric data can be extremely large, and requires specialized data formats to store it efficiently, particularly if the volume is *sparse* (with empty regions that do not contain data).
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Before rendering, level sets for volumetric data can be extracted and converted into a mesh of triangles, e.g. by using the marching cubes algorithm.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Algorithms have also been developed that work directly with volumetric data, for example to render realistic depictions of the way light is scattered and absorbed by clouds and smoke, and this type of volumetric rendering is used extensively in visual effects for movies.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] When rendering lower-resolution volumetric data without interpolation, the individual cubes or "voxels" may be visible, an effect sometimes used deliberately for game graphics.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Photographs of real world objects can be incorporated into a rendered scene by using them as textures for 3D objects.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Photos of a scene can also be stitched together to create panoramic images or environment maps, which allow the scene to be rendered very efficiently but only from a single viewpoint.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Scanning of real objects and scenes using structured light or lidar produces point clouds consisting of the coordinates of millions of individual points in space, sometimes along with color information.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] These point clouds may either be rendered directly or converted into meshes before rendering.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A more recent, experimental approach is description of scenes using radiance fields which define the color, intensity, and direction of incoming light at each point in space.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] (This is conceptually similar to, but not identical to, the light field recorded by a hologram.) For any useful resolution, the amount of data in a radiance field is so large that it is impractical to represent it directly as volumetric data, and an approximation function must be found.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Neural networks are typically used to generate and evaluate these approximations, sometimes using video frames, or a collection of photographs of a scene taken at different angles, as "training data".
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Algorithms related to neural networks have recently been used to find approximations of a scene as 3D Gaussians.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The resulting representation is similar to a point cloud, except that it uses fuzzy, partially-transparent blobs of varying dimensions and orientations instead of points.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] As with neural radiance fields, these approximations are often generated from photographs or video frames.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The output of rendering may be displayed immediately on the screen (many times a second, in the case of real-time rendering such as games) or saved in a raster graphics file format such as JPEG or PNG.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] High-end rendering applications commonly use the OpenEXR file format, which can represent finer gradations of colors and high dynamic range lighting, allowing tone mapping or other adjustments to be applied afterwards without loss of quality.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The output of a renderer sometimes includes more than just RGB color values.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Transparency information can be included, allowing rendered foreground objects to be composited with photographs or video.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] It is also sometimes useful to store the contributions of different lights, or of specular and diffuse lighting, as separate channels, so lighting can be adjusted after rendering.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The OpenEXR format allows storing many channels of data in a single file.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Renderers such as Blender and Pixar RenderMan support a large variety of configurable values called Arbitrary Output Variables (AOVs).
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Choosing how to render a 3D scene usually involves trade-offs between speed, memory usage, and realism (although realism is not always desired).
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The **algorithms** developed over the years follow a loose progression, with more advanced methods becoming practical as computing power and memory capacity increased.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Multiple techniques may be used for a single final image.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] An important distinction is between image order algorithms, which iterate over pixels in the image, and object order algorithms, which iterate over objects in the scene.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For simple scenes, object order is usually more efficient, as there are fewer objects than pixels.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] algorithms that also support filled shapes.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In principle, any 2D vector graphics renderer can be used to render 3D objects by first projecting them onto a 2D image plane.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Different realistic or stylized effects can be obtained by coloring the pixels covered by the objects in different ways.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rasterization is usually synonymous with "object order" rendering (as described above).
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It can be used to implement "image order" rendering by casting a ray for each pixel, and finding a corresponding point in the scene.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] , requiring a varying number of ray casting operations for each path.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] is usually in the domain of path tracing.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] approach that breaks surfaces in the scene into pieces, and estimates the amount of light that each piece receives from light sources, or indirectly from other surfaces.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] of each surface is known, the scene can be rendered using rasterization or ray tracing.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] , giving ray tracing a rigorous mathematical foundation.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Each of the above approaches has many variations, and there is some overlap.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Path tracing may be considered either a distinct technique or a particular type of ray tracing.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Note that the usage of terminology related to ray tracing and path tracing has changed significantly over time.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray marching is a family of algorithms, used by ray casting, for finding intersections between a ray and a complex object, such as a volumetric dataset or a surface defined by a signed distance function.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It is not, by itself, a rendering method, but it can be incorporated into ray tracing and path tracing, and is used by rasterization to implement screen-space reflection and other effects.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A technique called photon mapping traces paths of photons from a light source to an object, accumulating data about irradiance which is then used during conventional ray tracing or path tracing.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rendering a scene using only rays traced from the light source to the camera is impractical, even though it corresponds more closely to reality, because a huge number of photons would need to be simulated, only a tiny fraction of which actually hit the camera.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Some authors call conventional ray tracing "backward" ray tracing because it traces the paths of photons backwards from the camera to the light source, and call following paths from the light source (as in photon mapping) "forward" ray tracing.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] However, sometimes the meaning of these terms is reversed.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Tracing rays starting at the light source can also be called *particle tracing* or *light tracing*, which avoids this ambiguity.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Real-time rendering, including video game graphics, typically uses rasterization, but increasingly combines it with ray tracing and path tracing.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] To enable realistic global illumination, real-time rendering often relies on pre-rendered ("baked") lighting for stationary objects.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For moving objects, it may use a technique called *light probes*, in which lighting is recorded by rendering omnidirectional views of the scene at chosen points in space (often points on a grid to allow easier interpolation).
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] These are similar to environment maps, but typically use a very low resolution or an approximation such as spherical harmonics.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The term *rasterization* (in a broad sense) encompasses many techniques used for 2D rendering and real-time 3D rendering.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] 3D animated films were rendered by rasterization before ray tracing and path tracing became practical.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A renderer combines rasterization with *geometry processing* (which is not specific to rasterization) and *pixel processing* which computes the RGB color values to be placed in the *framebuffer* for display.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Historically, 3D rasterization used algorithms like the *Warnock algorithm* and *scanline rendering* (also called "scan-conversion"), which can handle arbitrary polygons and can rasterize many shapes simultaneously.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Although such algorithms are still important for 2D rendering, 3D rendering now usually divides shapes into triangles and rasterizes them individually using simpler methods.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] High-performance algorithms exist for rasterizing 2D lines, including anti-aliased lines, as well as ellipses and filled triangles.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] An important special case of 2D rasterization is text rendering, which requires careful anti-aliasing and rounding of coordinates to avoid distorting the letterforms and preserve spacing, density, and sharpness.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] After 3D coordinates have been projected onto the image plane, rasterization is primarily a 2D problem, but the 3rd dimension necessitates *hidden surface removal*.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Early computer graphics used geometric algorithms or ray casting to remove the hidden portions of shapes, or used the *painter's algorithm*, which sorts shapes by depth (distance from camera) and renders them from back to front.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Depth sorting was later avoided by incorporating depth comparison into the scanline rendering algorithm.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The *z-buffer* algorithm performs the comparisons indirectly by including a depth or "z" value in the framebuffer.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A pixel is only covered by a shape if that shape's z value is lower (indicating closer to the camera) than the z value currently in the buffer.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The z-buffer requires additional memory (an expensive resource at the time it was invented) but simplifies the rasterization code and permits multiple passes.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Memory is now faster and more plentiful, and a z-buffer is almost always used for real-time rendering.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A drawback of the basic z-buffer algorithm is that each pixel ends up either entirely covered by a single object or filled with the background color, causing jagged edges in the final image.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Early *anti-aliasing* approaches addressed this by detecting when a pixel is partially covered by a shape, and calculating the covered area.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The A-buffer (and other supersampling and multi-sampling techniques) solve the problem less precisely but with higher performance.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For real-time 3D graphics, it has become common to use complicated heuristics (and even neural-networks) to perform anti-aliasing.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In 3D rasterization, color is usually determined by a *pixel shader* or *fragment shader*, a small program that is run for each pixel.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Until relatively recently, Pixar used rasterization for rendering its animated films.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Unlike the renderers commonly used for real-time graphics, the Reyes rendering system in Pixar's RenderMan software was optimized for rendering very small (pixel-sized) polygons, and incorporated stochastic sampling techniques more typically associated with ray tracing.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] One of the simplest ways to render a 3D scene is to test if a ray starting at the viewpoint (the "eye" or "camera") intersects any of the geometric shapes in the scene, repeating this test using a different ray direction for each pixel.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This method, called *ray casting*, was important in early computer graphics, and is a fundamental building block for more advanced algorithms.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray casting can be used to render shapes defined by *constructive solid geometry* (CSG) operations.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Early ray casting experiments include the work of Arthur Appel in the 1960s.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Appel rendered shadows by casting an additional ray from each visible surface point towards a light source.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] He also tried rendering the density of illumination by casting random rays from the light source towards the object and plotting the intersection points (similar to the later technique called *photon mapping*).
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] When rendering scenes containing many objects, testing the intersection of a ray with every object becomes very expensive.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Special data structures are used to speed up this process by allowing large numbers of objects to be excluded quickly (such as objects behind the camera).
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] These structures are analogous to database indexes for finding the relevant objects.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The most common are the *bounding volume hierarchy* (BVH), which stores a pre-computed bounding box or sphere for each branch of a tree of objects, and the *k-d tree* which recursively divides space into two parts.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Recent GPUs include hardware acceleration for BVH intersection tests.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] K-d trees are a special case of *binary space partitioning*, which was frequently used in early computer graphics (it can also generate a rasterization order for the painter's algorithm).
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] *Octrees*, another historically popular technique, are still often used for volumetric data.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Geometric formulas are sufficient for finding the intersection of a ray with shapes like spheres, polygons, and polyhedra, but for most curved surfaces there is no analytic solution, or the intersection is difficult to compute accurately using limited precision floating point numbers.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Root-finding algorithms such as Newton's method can sometimes be used.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] To avoid these complications, curved surfaces are often approximated as meshes of triangles.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Volume rendering (e.g. rendering clouds and smoke), and some surfaces such as fractals, may require ray marching instead of basic ray casting.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray casting can be used to render an image by tracing light rays backwards from a simulated camera.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] After finding a point on a surface where a ray originated, another ray is traced towards the light source to determine if anything is casting a shadow on that point.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] If there are multiple light sources, brightness contributions of the lights are added together.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For color images, calculations are repeated for multiple wavelengths of light (e.g. red, green, and blue).
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray tracing usually performs anti-aliasing by taking the average of multiple samples for each pixel.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It may also use multiple samples for effects like depth of field and motion blur.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] If evenly spaced ray directions or times are used for each of these features, many rays are required, and some aliasing will remain.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] *Cook-style*, *stochastic*, or *Monte Carlo ray tracing* avoids this problem by using random sampling instead of evenly spaced samples.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This type of ray tracing is commonly called *distributed ray tracing*, or *distribution ray tracing* because it samples rays from probability distributions.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Distribution ray tracing can also render realistic "soft" shadows from large lights by using a random sample of points on the light when testing for shadowing, and it can simulate chromatic aberration by sampling multiple wavelengths from the spectrum of light.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Real surface materials reflect small amounts of light in almost every direction because they have small (or microscopic) bumps and grooves.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A distribution ray tracer can simulate this by sampling possible ray directions, which allows rendering blurry reflections from glossy and metallic surfaces.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] However, if this procedure is repeated recursively to simulate realistic indirect lighting, and if more than one sample is taken at each surface point, the tree of rays quickly becomes huge.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Another kind of ray tracing, called *path tracing*, handles indirect light more efficiently, avoiding branching, and ensures that the distribution of all possible paths from a light source to the camera is sampled in an unbiased way.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray tracing was often used for rendering reflections in animated films, until path tracing became standard for film rendering.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Films such as Shrek 2 and Monsters University also used distribution ray tracing or path tracing to precompute indirect illumination for a scene or frame prior to rendering it using rasterization.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Advances in GPU technology have made real-time ray tracing possible in games, although it is currently almost always used in combination with rasterization.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This enables visual effects that are difficult with only rasterization, including reflection from curved surfaces and interreflective objects, and shadows that are accurate over a wide range of distances and surface orientations.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray tracing support is included in recent versions of the graphics APIs used by games, such as DirectX, Metal, and Vulkan.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray tracing has been used to render simulated black holes, and the appearance of objects moving at close to the speed of light, by taking spacetime curvature and relativistic effects into account during light ray simulation.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Radiosity (named after the radiometric quantity of the same name) is a method for rendering objects illuminated by light bouncing off rough or matte surfaces.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This type of illumination is called *indirect light*, *environment lighting*, *diffuse lighting*, or *diffuse interreflection*, and the problem of rendering it realistically is called *global illumination*.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rasterization and basic forms of ray tracing (other than distribution ray tracing and path tracing) can only roughly approximate indirect light, e.g. by adding a uniform "ambient" lighting amount chosen by the artist.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Radiosity techniques are also suited to rendering scenes with *area lights* such as rectangular fluorescent lighting panels, which are difficult for rasterization and traditional ray tracing.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In the original radiosity method (first proposed in 1984) now called *classical radiosity*, surfaces and lights in the scene are split into pieces called *patches*, a process called *meshing* (this step makes it a finite element method).
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The rendering code must then determine what fraction of the light being emitted or diffusely reflected (scattered) by each patch is received by each other patch.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] These fractions are called *form factors* or *view factors* (first used in engineering to model radiative heat transfer).
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The form factors are multiplied by the albedo of the receiving surface and put in a matrix.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The lighting in the scene can then be expressed as a matrix equation (or equivalently a system of linear equations) that can be solved by methods from linear algebra.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Solving the radiosity equation gives the total amount of light emitted and reflected by each patch, which is divided by area to get a value called *radiosity* that can be used when rasterizing or ray tracing to determine the color of pixels corresponding to visible parts of the patch.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For real-time rendering, this value (or more commonly the irradiance, which does not depend on local surface albedo) can be pre-computed and stored in a texture (called an *irradiance map*) or stored as vertex data for 3D models.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This feature was used in architectural visualization software to allow real-time walk-throughs of a building interior after computing the lighting.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The large size of the matrices used in classical radiosity (the square of the number of patches) causes problems for realistic scenes.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Practical implementations may use Jacobi or Gauss-Seidel iterations, which is equivalent (at least in the Jacobi case) to simulating the propagation of light one bounce at a time until the amount of light remaining (not yet absorbed by surfaces) is insignificant.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Form factors may be recomputed when they are needed, to avoid storing a complete matrix in memory.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The quality of rendering is often determined by the size of the patches, e.g. very fine meshes are needed to depict the edges of shadows accurately.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] An important improvement is *hierarchical radiosity*, which uses a coarser mesh (larger patches) for simulating the transfer of light between surfaces that are far away from one another, and adaptively sub-divides the patches as needed.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This allows radiosity to be used for much larger and more complex scenes.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Alternative and extended versions of the radiosity method support non-Lambertian surfaces, such as glossy surfaces and mirrors, and sometimes use volumes or "clusters" of objects as well as surface patches.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Simplified and partially precomputed versions of radiosity are widely used for real-time rendering, combined with techniques such as *octree radiosity* that store approximations of the light field.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] As part of the approach known as *physically based rendering*, **path tracing** has become the dominant technique for rendering realistic scenes, including effects for movies.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For example, the popular open source 3D software Blender uses path tracing in its Cycles renderer.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Like *distributed ray tracing*, path tracing is a kind of *stochastic* or *randomized* ray tracing that uses Monte Carlo or Quasi-Monte Carlo integration.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It was proposed and named in 1986 by Jim Kajiya in the same paper as the rendering equation.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Kajiya suggested reducing the noise present in the output images by using *stratified sampling* and *importance sampling* for making random decisions such as choosing which ray to follow at each step of a path.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Even with these techniques, path tracing would not have been practical for film rendering, using computers available at the time, because the computational cost of generating enough samples to reduce variance to an acceptable level was too high.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Monster House, the first feature film rendered entirely using path tracing, was not released until 20 years later.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In its basic form, path tracing is inefficient (requiring too many samples) for rendering caustics and scenes where light enters indirectly through narrow spaces.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Attempts were made to address these weaknesses in the 1990s.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] *Metropolis light transport* samples paths by modifying paths that were previously traced, spending more time exploring paths that are similar to other "bright" paths, which increases the chance of discovering even brighter paths.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] *Multiple importance sampling* provides a way to reduce variance when combining samples from more than one sampling method, particularly when some samples are much noisier than the others.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This later work was summarized and expanded upon in Eric Veach's 1997 PhD thesis, which helped raise interest in path tracing in the computer graphics community.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The Arnold renderer, first released in 1998, proved that path tracing was practical for rendering frames for films, and that there was a demand for unbiased and physically based rendering in the film industry; other commercial and open source path tracing renderers began appearing.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Computational cost was addressed by rapid advances in CPU and cluster performance.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Path tracing's relative simplicity and its nature as a Monte Carlo method (sampling hundreds or thousands of paths per pixel) have made it attractive to implement on a GPU, especially on recent GPUs that support ray tracing acceleration technology such as Nvidia's RTX and OptiX.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] However bidirectional path tracing and Metropolis light transport are more difficult to implement efficiently on a GPU.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Techniques have been developed to denoise the output of path tracing, reducing the number of paths required to achieve acceptable quality, at the risk of losing some detail or introducing small-scale artifacts that are more objectionable than noise.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Neural networks are now widely used for this purpose.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Research into improving path tracing continues.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Many variations of bidirectional path tracing and Metropolis light transport have been explored, and ways of combining path tracing with photon mapping.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Recent *path guiding* approaches construct approximations of the light field probability distribution in each volume of space, so paths can be sampled more effectively.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] By combining denoising and hardware ray tracing acceleration, it is now practical to use path tracing for real-time rendering.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Due to performance constraints, biased techniques such as a radiance cache may be incorporated.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Spatiotemporal reservoir resampling (ReSTIR) aims to improve the quality of real-time path tracing and allow more complex lighting by reusing samples (paths) from previous frames and adjacent pixels.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] As of 2003, machine learning (ML) techniques were being used in other areas of computer graphics, such as texture synthesis, fitting surfaces to point clouds, and fitting curves to motion capture data.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The use of ML for rendering expanded with the availability of GPUs that can evaluate neural networks (especially convolutional neural networks) quickly.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Neural networks and Gaussian mixture models have been used in conjunction with rendering techniques such as path tracing to encode bidirectional reflectance distribution functions (BRDFs), or to encode cached radiance at points in space (for biased acceleration of rendering or for path guiding).
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Neural radiance fields (NeRFs) take the latter approach to an extreme, encoding radiance at all points in a volume, and using evaluation of this approximation as the primary rendering method.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] One of the most widely used applications of machine learning in rendering is denoising of path traced images (in practice, most path tracing now likely uses such a denoiser).
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Denoisers specialized for real-time rendering can work with very low sample counts and improve temporal coherence to reduce flickering.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rendering is usually limited by available computing power and memory bandwidth, and so specialized hardware has been developed to speed it up ("accelerate" it), particularly for real-time rendering.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Hardware features such as a framebuffer for raster graphics are required to display the output of rendering smoothly in real time.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Hardware acceleration does not replace the use of software for rendering, rather it speeds up selected operations or calculations using dedicated circuits, or runs portions of the software's code on a different type of processor.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In the era of vector monitors (also called *calligraphic displays*), a display processing unit (DPU) was a dedicated CPU or coprocessor that maintained a list of visual elements and redrew them continuously on the screen by controlling an electron beam.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Advanced DPUs such as Evans & Sutherland's Line Drawing System-1 (and later models produced into the 1980s) incorporated 3D coordinate transformation features to accelerate rendering of wire-frame images.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Evans & Sutherland also made the Digistar planetarium projection system, which was a vector display that could render both stars and wire-frame graphics (the vector-based Digistar and Digistar II were used in many planetariums, and a few may still be in operation).
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A Digistar prototype was used for rendering 3D star fields for the film Star Trek II: The Wrath of Khan – some of the first 3D computer graphics sequences ever seen in a feature film.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Shaded 3D graphics rendering in the 1970s and early 1980s was usually implemented on general-purpose computers, such as the PDP-10 used by researchers at the University of Utah.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It was difficult to speed up using specialized hardware because it involves a pipeline of complex steps, requiring data addressing, decision-making, and computation capabilities typically only provided by CPUs (although dedicated circuits for speeding up particular operations were proposed ).
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Supercomputers or specially designed multi-CPU computers or clusters were sometimes used for ray tracing.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Clark and Marc Hannah designed the Geometry Engine, a VLSI chip for performing some of the steps of the 3D rasterization pipeline, and started the company Silicon Graphics (SGI) to commercialize this technology.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Home computers and game consoles in the 1980s contained graphics coprocessors that were capable of scrolling and filling areas of the display, and drawing sprites and lines, though they were not useful for rendering realistic images.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Towards the end of the 1980s PC graphics cards and arcade games with 3D rendering acceleration began to appear, and in the 1990s such technology became commonplace.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Today, even low-power mobile processors typically incorporate 3D graphics acceleration features.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The 3D graphics accelerators of the 1990s evolved into modern GPUs.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] GPUs are general-purpose processors, like CPUs, but they are designed for tasks that can be broken into many small, similar, mostly independent sub-tasks (such as rendering individual pixels) and performed in parallel.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Due to their origins, GPUs typically still provide specialized hardware acceleration for some steps of a traditional 3D rasterization pipeline, including hidden surface removal using a z-buffer, and texture mapping with mipmaps, but these features are no longer always used.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Recent GPUs have features to accelerate finding the intersections of rays with a bounding volume hierarchy, to help speed up all variants of ray tracing and path tracing, as well as neural network acceleration features sometimes useful for rendering.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rendering algorithms will run efficiently on a GPU only if they can be implemented using small groups of threads that perform mostly the same operations.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] As an example of code that meets this requirement: when rendering a small square of pixels in a simple ray-traced image, all threads will likely be intersecting rays with the same object and performing the same lighting computations.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For performance and architectural reasons, GPUs run groups of around 16-64 threads called *warps* or *wavefronts* in lock-step (all threads in the group are executing the same instructions at the same time).
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] If not all threads in the group need to run particular blocks of code (due to conditions) then some threads will be idle, or the results of their computations will be discarded, causing degraded performance.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Historically, the term *hardware rendering* (possibly an abbreviation of "hardware accelerated rendering" or "hardware-assisted rendering") was sometimes used to mean rendering using a hardware-accelerated rasterization pipeline (typically for real-time rendering).
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In contrast, *software rendering* meant offline rendering using software that was not limited by the capabilities of graphics hardware, and could use more realistic and higher quality techniques.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Both hardware and software have evolved, and although these terms are still used, their meaning may now be context-dependent.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] When OpenGL and Direct3D were introduced in the 1990s, there was a need to use these APIs on computers that did not have hardware acceleration for 3D graphics.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] "Fallback" rendering implementations were provided that did not require special hardware, and these are sometimes called "software renderers" (today hardware acceleration is almost always available, and these CPU-only implementations are used primarily for testing).
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] More recently, "software rendering" may also mean rendering that does not use graphics APIs such as OpenGL, Metal, Direct3D, or Vulkan.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Types of renderers that in the past might have been called "software renderers" (e.g. path tracing renderers used for offline rendering for movies) now commonly use GPU acceleration, often via APIs such as CUDA or OpenCL, which are not graphics-specific.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Since these latter APIs allow running C++ code on a GPU, it is now possible to run the same rendering code on either a CPU or GPU.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The following is a rough timeline of frequently mentioned rendering techniques, including areas of current research.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Note that even in cases where an idea was named in a specific paper, there were almost always multiple researchers or teams working in the same area (including earlier related work).
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] When a method is first proposed it is often very inefficient, and it takes additional research and practical efforts to turn it into a useful technique.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The list focuses on academic research and does not include hardware.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] In computer graphics, a **shader** is a programmable operation which is applied to data as it moves through the rendering pipeline.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] Shaders act on data such as vertices and primitives, generate or morph geometries and fragments, and calculate the colors in a rendered image.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] Shaders can execute a wide variety of operations.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] In modern real-time computer graphics, shaders are run on graphics processing units (GPUs) - dedicated hardware which provide parallel execution of programs.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] Because image rendering is an embarrassingly parallel problem (having an Amdahl's index of one), shaders benefit greatly from parallel computing, such as SIMD hardware.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] The drive for faster rendering has produced highly parallel processors, like GPUs, which are now used for general-purpose computing.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] Shaders used for general purposes are commonly called *compute shaders*.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] The term "shader" was first introduced to the public by Pixar with version 3.0 of their RenderMan Interface Specification, originally published in May 1988.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] As graphics processing units evolved, major graphics software libraries such as OpenGL and Direct3D began to support shaders.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] The first shader-capable GPUs only supported pixel shading, but vertex shaders were quickly introduced once developers realized the power of shaders.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] The first video card with a programmable pixel shader was the Nvidia GeForce 3 (NV20), released in 2001.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] Geometry shaders were introduced with Direct3D 10 and OpenGL 3.2.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] Graphics hardware evolved toward a unified shader model, making all shaders equal.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] The traditional use of shaders is to operate on data in the graphics pipeline to control the rendering of an image.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] Graphics shaders are classified according to their position in the pipeline, the data being manipulated, and the graphics API being used.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] Vertex shaders are run once for each 3D vertex given to the graphics processor.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] The purpose is to transform each vertex's 3D position in virtual space to the 2D coordinate at which it appears on the screen (as well as a depth value for the Z-buffer).
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] Vertex shaders can manipulate properties such as position, color and texture coordinates, but cannot create new vertices.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] The output of the vertex shader goes to the next stage in the pipeline, which is either a geometry shader if present, or the rasterizer.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] Vertex shaders can enable powerful control over the details of position, movement, lighting, and color in any scene involving 3D models.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] Geometry shaders were introduced in Direct3D 10 and OpenGL 3.2; formerly available in OpenGL 2.0+ with the use of extensions.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] This type of shader can generate new graphics primitives, such as points, lines, and triangles, from those primitives that were sent to the beginning of the graphics pipeline.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] Geometry shader programs are executed after vertex shaders.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] They take as input a whole primitive, possibly with adjacency information.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] For example, when operating on triangles, the three vertices are the geometry shader's input.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] The shader can then emit zero or more primitives, which are rasterized and their fragments ultimately passed to a pixel shader.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] Typical uses of a geometry shader include point sprite generation, geometry tessellation, shadow volume extrusion, and single pass rendering to a cube map.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] A typical real-world example of the benefits of geometry shaders would be automatic mesh complexity modification.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] A series of line strips representing control points for a curve are passed to the geometry shader and depending on the complexity required the shader can automatically generate extra lines each of which provides a better approximation of a curve.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] model rendered using fragment shaders with different outputs: solid white, applied texture, physically based shading.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] Fragment shaders, also known as **pixel shaders**, compute color and other attributes of each "fragment": a unit of rendering work affecting at most a single output pixel.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] The simplest kinds of pixel shaders output one screen pixel as a color value; more complex shaders with multiple inputs/outputs are also possible.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] Pixel shaders range from simply always outputting the same color, to applying a lighting value, to doing bump mapping, shadows, specular highlights, translucency and other phenomena.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] They can alter the depth of the fragment (for Z-buffering), or output more than one color if multiple render targets are active.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] In 3D graphics, a pixel shader alone cannot produce some kinds of complex effects because it operates only on a single fragment, without knowledge of a scene's geometry (i.e. vertex data).
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] However, pixel shaders do have knowledge of the screen coordinate being drawn, and can sample the screen and nearby pixels if the contents of the entire screen are passed as a texture to the shader.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] This technique can enable a wide variety of two-dimensional postprocessing effects such as blur, or edge detection/enhancement for cartoon/cel shaders.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] Pixel shaders may also be applied in *intermediate* stages to any two-dimensional images—sprites or textures—in the pipeline, whereas vertex shaders always require a 3D scene.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] For instance, a pixel shader is the only kind of shader that can act as a postprocessor or filter for a video stream after it has been rasterized.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] OpenGL 4.0 and Direct3D 11 introduced a new shader class called a tessellation shader.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] The function can be related to a variety of variables, most notably the distance from the viewing camera to allow active level-of-detail scaling.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] This allows objects close to the camera to have fine detail, while further away ones can have more coarse meshes, yet seem comparable in quality.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] It also can drastically reduce required mesh bandwidth by allowing meshes to be refined once inside the shader units instead of down-sampling very complex ones from memory.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] Some algorithms can up-sample any arbitrary mesh, while others allow for "hinting" in meshes to dictate the most characteristic vertices and edges.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] Circa 2017, the AMD Vega microarchitecture added support for a new shader stage—primitive shaders—somewhat akin to compute shaders with access to the data necessary to process geometry.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] Nvidia introduced mesh and task shaders with its Turing microarchitecture in 2018 which are also modelled after compute shaders.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] Nvidia Turing is the world's first GPU microarchitecture that supports mesh shading through DirectX 12 Ultimate API, several months before Ampere RTX 30 series was released.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] In 2020, AMD and Nvidia released RDNA 2 and Ampere microarchitectures which both support mesh shading through DirectX 12 Ultimate.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] These mesh shaders allow the GPU to handle more complex algorithms, offloading more work from the CPU to the GPU, and in algorithm intense rendering, increasing the frame rate of or number of triangles in a scene by an order of magnitude.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] Intel announced that Intel Arc Alchemist GPUs shipping in Q1 2022 will support mesh shaders.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] Ray tracing shaders are supported by Microsoft via DirectX Raytracing, by Khronos Group via Vulkan, GLSL, and SPIR-V, by Apple via Metal.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] Nvidia and AMD called the parts of the hardware responsible for executing these shaders "ray tracing cores".
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] Compute kernels are routines compiled for high throughput accelerators (such as graphics processing units (GPUs), digital signal processors (DSPs), or field-programmable gate arrays (FPGAs)), separate from but used by a main program (typically running on a central processing unit).
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] They may be specified by a separate programming language such as "OpenCL C", as "compute shaders" written in a shading language, or embedded directly in application code written in a high level language.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] Compute kernels roughly correspond to inner loops when implementing algorithms in traditional languages (except there is no implied sequential operation), or to code passed to internal iterators.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] Microsoft support this as DirectCompute.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] This single program, multiple data programming paradigm maps well to vector processors: there is an assumption that each invocation of a kernel within a batch is independent, allowing for data parallel execution.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] However, atomic operations may sometimes be used for synchronization between elements (for interdependent work), in some scenarios.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] Individual invocations are given indices (in 1 or more dimensions) from which arbitrary addressing of buffer data may be performed (including scatter gather operations), so long as the non-overlapping assumption is respected.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] The Vulkan API provides the intermediate SPIR-V representation to describe *both* graphical shaders, and compute kernels in a language independent and machine independent manner.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] The intention is to facilitate language evolution and provide a more natural ability to leverage GPU compute capabilities, in line with hardware developments such as Unified Memory Architecture and Heterogeneous System Architecture.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] This allows closer cooperation between a CPU and GPU.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] Much work has been done in the field of Kernel generation through LLMs as a means of optimizing code.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] KernelBench, created by the Scaling Intelligence Lab at Stanford, provides a framework to evaluate the ability of LLMs to generate efficient GPU kernels.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] Cognition has created Kevin 32-B to create efficient CUDA kernels which is currently the highest performing model on KernelBench.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] Tensor shaders are accelerator programs that deal with matrix operations on large arrays, a type of operation commonly used in neural network-based AI.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] Tensor shaders are supported by Microsoft via DirectML, by Khronos Group via OpenVX, by Apple via Core ML, by Google via TensorFlow, by Linux Foundation via ONNX.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] Nvidia and AMD called the parts of the hardware responsible for executing these shaders "tensor cores".
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] Several programming languages exist specifically for writing shaders, and which is used can depend on the target environment.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] The shading language for OpenGL is GLSL, and Direct3D uses HLSL.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] The Metal framework, used by Apple devices, has its own shading language called Metal Shading Language.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] Increasingly in modern graphics APIs, shaders are compiled into SPIR-V, an intermediate language, before they are distributed to the end user.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] This standard allows more flexible choice of shading language, regardless of target platform.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] First supported by Vulkan and OpenGL, SPIR-V is also being adopted by Direct3D.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] The graph is then compiled into a shader.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] In web development contexts, visual and component-based shader tools have also emerged.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/shader] Platforms such as shaders.com provide component-driven composition of shaders for integration into frontend frameworks including Vue, React, and Svelte, while tools such as Shadertoy and FragCoord.xyz focus on lower-level shader authoring and debugging.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/viewing-frustum] In 3D computer graphics, a **viewing frustum** or **view frustum** is the region of space in the modeled world that may appear on the screen; it is the field of view of a perspective virtual camera system.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/viewing-frustum] The view frustum is typically obtained by taking a geometrical frustum—that is a truncation with parallel planes—of the **pyramid of vision**, which is the adaptation of (idealized) *cone of vision* that a camera or eye would have to the rectangular viewports typically used in computer graphics.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/viewing-frustum] Some authors use *pyramid of vision* as a synonym for view frustum itself, i.e. consider it truncated.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/viewing-frustum] The exact shape of this region varies depending on what kind of camera lens is being simulated, but typically it is a frustum of a rectangular pyramid (hence the name).
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/viewing-frustum] The planes that cut the frustum perpendicular to the viewing direction are called the *near plane* and the *far plane*.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/viewing-frustum] Objects closer to the camera than the near plane or beyond the far plane are not drawn.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/viewing-frustum] Sometimes, the far plane is placed infinitely far away from the camera so all objects within the frustum are drawn regardless of their distance from the camera.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/viewing-frustum] Viewing-frustum culling is the process of removing from the rendering process those objects that lie completely outside the viewing frustum.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/viewing-frustum] Rendering these objects would be a waste of resources since they are not directly visible.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/viewing-frustum] To make culling fast, it is usually done using bounding volumes surrounding the objects rather than the objects themselves.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/viewing-frustum] the view-up vector – the vector on the view plane that indicates the upward direction.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/viewing-frustum] the viewing reference point – a point located on the view plane, and the origin of the VRC.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/viewing-frustum] the projection reference point – the point where the image is projected from, for parallel projection, the PRP is at infinity.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/viewing-frustum] the viewing-reference coordinate system.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/viewing-frustum] The geometry is defined by a field of view angle (in the 'y' direction), as well as an aspect ratio.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/viewing-frustum] Further, a set of z-planes define the **near and far bounds** of the frustum.
[src:gpu-driven-rendering/viewing-frustum] Together this information can be used to calculate a projection matrix for rendering transformation in a graphics pipeline.
